[{"location":"DeBoer/#DeBoer-Model-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer Model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"DeBoer, R. W., Karemaker, J. M., & Strackee, J. (1987). Hemodynamic fluctuations and baroreflex sensitivity in humans: a beat-to-beat model. American Journal of Physiology-Heart and Circulatory Physiology, 253(3), H680-H689. (DOI)","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Theory-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Theory","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Effective-pressure:-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Effective pressure:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"The systolic pressure is transformed to be in accordance with the sigmoid-shaped activation curve of the baroreflex. The constant S_0 defines the working point.","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"S_n^star = f(S_n)hspace5mmtextwith hspace5mm f(S_n) = S_0 + 18textatanleft(fracS_n -S_0 18right)","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Baroreflex-on-Heart-Rate-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Baroreflex on Heart Rate","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"The transfer function G_a(z) relates the effective systolic pressure to the RR interval. It models fast vagally mediated and slower, sympathetic, baroreflex effects.","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"I_n = G_a (z) S_n^star","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Baroreflex-on-Peripheral-Resistance-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Baroreflex on Peripheral Resistance","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"The peripheral resistance is influenced by the baroreflex mediated through the sympathetic nervous system reflected in the transfer function G_b(z). T_0 is an empirical offset constant (around 3000 ms).","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"T_ n  = R_n C = T_ 0  + G_b(z)S_n^star","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Properties-of-Myocardium-and-Respiration-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Properties of Myocardium & Respiration","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"Starling's law governs the pulse pressure through the coupling constant gamma. Respiration also enters through the pulse pressure, modeled as a sine. ","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"P_ n  = gamma I_n  + A_rhosin(2pi f_rho t) hspace5mm textwith hspace5mm t = sum I_n","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Windkessel-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Windkessel","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"Diastolic pressure is derived from the two-element Windkessel model.","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"D_ n  = S_n exp left( - fracI_n T_n  right)","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Time-Propagation-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Time Propagation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"The next beat is calculated through the standard relation:","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"S_n+1 = P_n + D_n","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#Usage-1","page":"DeBoer","title":"Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"DeBoerModel","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#CardioModels.DeBoerModel","page":"DeBoer","title":"CardioModels.DeBoerModel","text":"DeBoerModel()\n\nA simple structure that stores a DeBoer-model. \n\nThe default initialization was taken from the original paper. When constructiong the model, single properties can be defined as keyword arguments.  The model has a state, if it was already used in predict!, otherwise a default is provided in predict or predict!.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> model = DeBoerModel()\nDeBoerModel\n  a0: Int64 9\n  ak: Array{Int64}((6,)) [0, 1, 2, 3, 2, 1]\n  c1: Int64 -1360\n  bk: Array{Int64}((6,)) [0, 2, 4, 6, 4, 2]\n  TStar: Int64 3585\n  γ: Float64 0.016\n  c2: Float64 32.2\n  c3: Float64 1.0957070684897647\n  A: Int64 3\n  fresp: Float64 0.3\n  resp: #30 (function of type Main.CardioModels.var\"#30#36\"{Int64, Float64})\n  noiseI: Distributions.Normal{Float64}\n  noiseS: Distributions.Normal{Float64}\n  operationPoint: Int64 120\n  F: #31 (function of type Main.CardioModels.var\"#31#37\"{Int64})\n  hasState: Bool false\n  S: Nothing nothing\n  Seff: Nothing nothing\n  D: Nothing nothing\n  I: Nothing nothing\n  T: Nothing nothing\n  ρ: Nothing nothing\n  time: Int64 0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"predict(::DeBoerModel, ::Int)","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#CardioModels.predict-Tuple{DeBoerModel, Int64}","page":"DeBoer","title":"CardioModels.predict","text":"predict(model::DeBoerModel, n::Int; burnIn::Int = 0)\n\nPredicts 'N' values of the cardiovascular variables for the respective model. With 'burnIn' a certain number af values can be dropped in the beginning.\n\nExamples\n\njulia  julia> S, D, I, T, ρ = predict(model, 100)    (S = [...], D = [...], I = [...], T = [...], ρ = [...])\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"DeBoer/#","page":"DeBoer","title":"DeBoer","text":"predict!(::DeBoerModel, ::Int)","category":"page"},{"location":"DeBoer/#CardioModels.predict!-Tuple{DeBoerModel, Int64}","page":"DeBoer","title":"CardioModels.predict!","text":"predict!(model::DeBoerModel, n::Int; burnIn::Int = 0)\n\nUpdates the state of the state of the model with the last predicted values.  Predicts 'N' values of the cardiovascular variables for the respective model and updates its state. With 'burnIn' a certain number af values can be dropped in the beginning.\n\nExamples\n\njulia  julia> S, D, I, T, ρ = predict!(model, 100)   (S = [...], D = [...], I = [...], T = [...], ρ = [...])   julia> model.hasState  true\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"Baselli/#Baselli-Model-1","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli Model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"Baselli, G., Cerutti, S., Civardi, S., Malliani, A., & Pagani, M. (1988). Cardiovascular variability signals: towards the identification of a closed-loop model of the neural control mechanisms. IEEE Transactions on Biomedical Engineering, 35(12), 1033-1046. (DOI))","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#Theory-1","page":"Baselli","title":"Theory","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"The model is defined through the following three equations, where G denotes an all-zero and M an all-pole transfer function:","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"beginaligned\nS_n = G_SS(z)S_n quad + quad G_SI(z)I_n quad  + quad G_Srho(z) rho_n  quad  + quad  M_S(z) w_S \nI_n = G_IS(z)S_n quad  + hspace29mm  G_Irho(z) rho_n quad  + quad  M_I(z) w_I\nrho_n = hspace76mmM_rho(z) w_rho\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"It can be identified from data as an ARXAR-model using the generalized least squares method (via arxar).","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#Usage-1","page":"Baselli","title":"Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"BaselliModel","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#CardioModels.BaselliModel","page":"Baselli","title":"CardioModels.BaselliModel","text":"BaselliModel()\n\nA simple structure that stores a Baselli-model in form of transfer functions. It has a recipe defined to get some bode plots. \n\nThe default initialization is not proper, to get a working model use 'getModel(sim)', which gives one of the four configurations from the original paper.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> model = getModel(1)\n[ Info: Simulation 1: Respiration enters on S (LF are generated in the S, S loop)\nBaselliModel...\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"The model can be plotted:","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"using Plots, CardioModels","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"model = getModel(1)\nplot(model)","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"Predefined models can be obtained with:","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"getModel","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#CardioModels.getModel","page":"Baselli","title":"CardioModels.getModel","text":"getModel(sim::Int)\n\nGives a proper Baselli-model taken from the original paper, where 'sim' can take the value from 1:4, with the meaning:\n\n1: Respiration enters on S (LF are generated in the S, S loop)\n2: Respiration enters on I (LF are generated in the S, S loop)\n3: The LF are generated by S regulating feedback in the S, S loop (respiration enters both on S and on I)\n4: LF are generated externally from the closed-loop system (i.e., via a central command-respiration enters both on S and on I)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"predict(::BaselliModel, ::Int)","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#CardioModels.predict-Tuple{BaselliModel, Int64}","page":"Baselli","title":"CardioModels.predict","text":"predict(model::BaselliModel, N::Int; burnIn::Int = 50)\n\nPredicts 'N' values of the cardiovascular variables for the respective model. With 'burnIn' a certain number af values can be dropped in the beginning.\n\nExamples\n\njulia  julia> S, I, ρ = predict(model, 100)    (S = [...], I = [...], ρ = [...])\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"fitBaselli","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#CardioModels.fitBaselli","page":"Baselli","title":"CardioModels.fitBaselli","text":"fitBaselli(S::Vector{<:Real}, I::Vector{<:Real}, ρ::Vector{<:Real}; ...)\n\nFit the Baselli model from measured or generated data.\n\nArguments\n\nS: Systolic blood pressure\nI: RR Interval series\nρ: Respiration\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\nna, nb, nc: order of the respective transfer functions, default to 10\niterations: maximum number of iterations, defaults to 10 \nδmin: minimum changes that defines convergence, defaults to 0.001\nverbose: get more information\nestimator: defaults to \\ least squares \n\nReturn\n\nReturns a BaselliModel from which physiological indices can be inferrede by postprocess()\n\nExample\n\n    model = getModel(1)\n    result = predict(model, 100)\n    modelEst = fitBaselli(result...)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"Baselli/#","page":"Baselli","title":"Baselli","text":"postprocess","category":"page"},{"location":"Baselli/#CardioModels.postprocess","page":"Baselli","title":"CardioModels.postprocess","text":"postprocess(M::BaselliModel, S::Vector{<:Real}, I::Vector{<:Real})\n\nExtract physiologically relevant indices from the Baselli model by means of post processing as defindes in:\n\nBaselli et al. (1994)  Model for the assessment of heart period and arterial pressure variability interactions and of respiration influences \n\nIndices\n\nα: Measure for baroreflex sensitivity\ngSI: Mechanical effects and properties of the myocardium, Starling's law\ngSS: Mechanical effects of blood pressure regulation (Windkessel)\nGssLF: Index of the contribution of AP regulation to the genesis of LF oscillations\nΘt/Θs: Respiratory effects\nPusLF/PutLF: Residual signals and detection of different L F sources \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"Karemaker/#Karemaker-Model-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker Model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"Karemaker, J. M. (1998). Testing the validity of LF/HF as measure of ‘sympathovagal balance’ in a computer model of cardiovascular control. Proceedings of the IX International Symposium on the Autonomic Nervous System.","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#Theory-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"Theory","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"A main feature of the model is that besides parasympathetic action through the baroreflex, sympathetic action is added. Sympathetic activity is triggered if the diastolic pressure falls below a reference value and influences heart rate, inotropy, and systemic resistance with some delay. In this way, a 0.1Hz oscillation is induced.","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#Sympathetic-activation-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"Sympathetic activation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"beginaligned\nSympD_n = 0 hspace18mm textif hspace5mm D_n  D_textref \nSympD_n = D_textref - D_n hspace5mm textif hspace5mm D_n leq D_textref\nSymp_n = textatan left(G_SA(z) cdot SympD_nright)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#Baroreflex-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"Baroreflex","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"I_n^star = a_1 S_n-1 + I_0 + w_I + A_rho^Isin(2pi f_rhot + phi) hspace5mm textif hspace5mmI_n-1  700 ms","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"I_n^star = a_2 S_n-2 + I_0 + w_I + A_rho^Isin(2pi f_rhot + phi) hspace5mm textif hspace5mmI_n-1 leq 700 ms","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"I_n = fracI_n^star1 + beta Symp_n","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"with beta the sympathetic 'force' on I","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"D_n = S_n expleft(frac-I_n R C (1 + delta Symp_n)right)","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"with RC the diastolic runoff and delta the sympathetic 'force' on D","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#Starling/Restitution-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"Starling/Restitution","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"P_n = (gamma I_n + P_0)(1+ varepsilon Symp_n) + w_P + A_rho^Psin(2pi f_rhot + phi)","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"with varepsilon the sympathetic 'force' on P (inotropy by symathetics and respiratory BP modulation) \nThe next systole is determined by S_n+1 = D_n + P_n ","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#Usage-1","page":"Karemaker","title":"Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"KaremakerModel","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#CardioModels.KaremakerModel","page":"Karemaker","title":"CardioModels.KaremakerModel","text":"KaremakerModel()\n\nA simple structure that stores a Karemaker-model. \n\nThe default initialization was taken from the original paper. When constructiong the model, single properties can be defined as keyword arguments. \n\nExamples\n\njulia> model = KaremakerModel()\nKaremakerModel\n  c: Float64 350.0\n  magn_int: Float64 10.0\n  r_int: Distributions.Normal{Float64}\n  A_resp: Float64 60.0\n  T_resp: Float64 3000.0\n  a1: Float64 9.0\n  a2: Float64 9.0\n  b_I: Float64 0.125\n  b_D: Float64 0.125\n  b_P: Float64 0.125\n  Dref: Float64 80.0\n  t_runoff: Float64 2000.0\n  offset: Float64 10.0\n  starling: Float64 0.016\n  magn_pulse: Float64 2.0\n  A_BP: Float64 3.0\n  w: Array{Float64}((6,)) [0.0, 0.01, 0.03, 0.03, 0.015, 0.005]\n  symp_set: Float64 0.5\n  symp_add: Array{Float64}((2,)) [-0.05, 0.2]\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"Karemaker/#","page":"Karemaker","title":"Karemaker","text":"predict(::KaremakerModel, ::Int)","category":"page"},{"location":"Karemaker/#CardioModels.predict-Tuple{KaremakerModel, Int64}","page":"Karemaker","title":"CardioModels.predict","text":"predict(model::KaremakerModel, n::Int; burnIn::Int = 0)\n\nPredicts 'N' values of the cardiovascular variables for the respective model. With 'burnIn' a certain number af values can be dropped in the beginning.\n\nExamples\n\njulia  julia> S, D, P, I, Symp, ρ = predict(model, 100)    (S = [...], D = [...], P = [...], I = [...], Symp = [...], ρ = [...])\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#CardioModels-1","page":"General","title":"CardioModels","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#Notation-1","page":"General","title":"Notation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"General","title":"General","text":"The following convention is used for cardiovascular variables:","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"General","title":"General","text":"I:  RR Intrval series\nS:  Systolic blood pressure\nD:  Diastolic blood pressure\nP:  Pulse Pressure\nrho\n:   Respiration\nT: Time constant as a measure of peripheral resistance R","category":"page"},{"location":"#","page":"General","title":"General","text":"The relation between different variables is shown in the below figure: (Image: Notation and relation of cardiovascular variables)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Models-1","page":"General","title":"Models","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"#","page":"General","title":"General","text":"Pages = [\n    \"DeBoer.md\",\n    \"Karemaker.md\",\n    \"Baselli.md\",\n]\nDepth = 1","category":"page"}]
